.TH "TILDR\-SECURITY" "1" "2026" "Tildr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
tildr\-security \[em] binary verification and release security for Tildr
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IP
.EX
gpg \-\-verify SHA256SUMS.asc
sha256sum \-c SHA256SUMS
.EE
.SH DESCRIPTION
All Tildr releases are signed with a GPG key held by the project
maintainers.
Verifying the signature before installation ensures the binary has not
been tampered with.
.SH PREREQUISITES
.IP \[bu] 2
GPG (GNU Privacy Guard) installed on your system
.IP \[bu] 2
The project\[cq]s public GPG key imported into your keyring
.SH IMPORTING THE PUBLIC KEY
Import the maintainer\[cq]s public key from a keyserver:
.IP
.EX
gpg \-\-keyserver keys.openpgp.org \-\-recv\-keys E6A5CC75350F3DCE
.EE
.PP
Or download and import it directly:
.IP
.EX
curl \-fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/orbitbits/pubkey/main/pubkey.asc \f[B]|\f[R] gpg \-\-import
.EE
.SH VERIFYING A RELEASE
After downloading the binary, \f[B]SHA256SUMS\f[R], and
\f[B]SHA256SUMS.asc\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]# Step 1: verify the GPG signature over SHA256SUMS\f[R]
gpg \-\-verify SHA256SUMS.asc

\f[I]# Step 2: verify the binary checksum\f[R]
sha256sum \-c SHA256SUMS
.EE
.PP
Both commands must succeed.
A valid run looks like:
.IP
.EX
gpg: Good signature from \[dq]William Canin <hello.williamcanin\[at]gmail.com>\[dq]
tildr\-0.1.0\-linux\-x86_64: OK
.EE
.SH WHAT THIS ENSURES
.TP
\f[B]Authenticity\f[R]
The release was produced by the project maintainers, verified by GPG
signature.
.TP
\f[B]Integrity\f[R]
The binary has not been modified or corrupted since it was signed,
verified by SHA256 checksum.
.TP
\f[B]Non\-repudiation\f[R]
The maintainers can be held accountable for the content of each release.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]SHA256SUMS\f[R]
Checksums file listing the SHA256 hash of each release artifact.
.TP
\f[I]SHA256SUMS.asc\f[R]
Detached GPG signature over the SHA256SUMS file.
